@vlad902 generally you don't want to run `!bench` before Mathlib CI passes because the benchmark won't have anything useful to say if CI doesn't succeed, and then it's just using up benchmarking resources for no reason. Therefore, you can add the `bench-after-CI` label, which will automatically benchmark the PR after CI completes successfully (so you don't have to remember to come back to `!bench` it yourself).

For right now, don't add this label, because CI might be successful.

(Note: this is not criticism, just informational.)

